prompt:
We run an ultimate tic-tac-toe ladder at the office and scoring disputes are getting silly — mostly about which board you're allowed to play in. I want a rules engine that settles it, C++20, stdlib only, in uttt.h and uttt.cpp:

    struct UTTT { /* your representation, default-constructible */ };

    void ut_init(UTTT *g);
    int  ut_to_move(const UTTT *g);
    int  ut_forced(const UTTT *g);
    int  ut_cell(const UTTT *g, int b, int c);
    int  ut_subwinner(const UTTT *g, int b);
    int  ut_winner(const UTTT *g);
    bool ut_play(UTTT *g, int b, int c);
    int  ut_replay(UTTT *g, const std::string &moves);

The macro grid is 9 sub-boards numbered 0..8 row-major; cells inside a board are 0..8 row-major too. X is 1 and moves first, O is 2.

The rules of the ladder, exactly:

- A move is (board b, cell c). It's legal only while the match is undecided, b and c are in range, cell c of board b is empty, board b is still OPEN — and b matches the forced board when there is one. Illegal moves change nothing and ut_play returns false.
- Sent-board rule: after a move at cell c, the opponent must play in board c. But if board c is closed, they get a free choice among all open boards. ut_forced reports the board the side to move must use, or -1 for free choice (including the very first move).
- A board closes the moment someone makes three in a row inside it (ut_subwinner returns 1 or 2) — its remaining empty cells are dead for the rest of the match — or when its ninth cell fills with no line, which is a drawn board (ut_subwinner 3). Open is 0.
- The match: a player who owns three boards in a macro row/column/diagonal wins (ut_winner 1 or 2). Drawn boards belong to NOBODY — they never help either player's macro line. If all nine boards close without a macro line, the match is a draw (ut_winner 3). Otherwise 0, still going.
- ut_cell returns 0/1/2 for a cell, -1 if either index is out of range.
- ut_replay resets to a fresh match and applies moves from a space-separated string of "b:c" tokens, returning -1 if all were legal, else the 0-based index of the first illegal move — with the legal prefix left standing.

test_uttt.cpp is the acceptance contract. It includes three full scripted games: a macro win on the diagonal, a 69-move match where every board closes and nobody wins, and my favourite regression — X owns boards 0 and 1 and board 2 fills up drawn, and half the office thought top-row-all-closed meant X had won. It does not. make test decides; test_uttt.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile are fixed.
